<font color="#FF0000">HOMECOMING</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 19 19:49:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art, it took almost thirty years for me to put mine in a case to display.  Mostly it was done by my sister who sent me the frame and said &quot;put them in this and show them with pride&quot;.  So being the smarter older brother I did that.  What precluded this was a visit from my sister and a conversation that we had.<br>
It started with my experiences in country.  And the conversation ended with tears and hugs.  It was strange that in all this time I had never thought about how my sister dealt with me being in viet nam while she was a junior in high school.  It was bad enough that she had to follow me through high school (two years behind) but then she had to deal with the comments, stares, and questions from her peers about her brother in viet nam.  The stories that she told me angered and shamed me; that I had never taken into account her reactions after I had returned.   We never had discussed these feeling for almost twenty-five years.  I finally, finally, came home when she said, &quot;Welcome home, Chet&quot;.
